Problem:
Write a function called `is_prime` that takes an integer as an argument and returns a Boolean value indicating whether the integer is prime or not. A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive natural number divisors other than 1 and itself.

Solution 1 (Python):

```python
def is_prime(n):
    """Return True if n is prime, False otherwise."""
    if n <= 1:
        return False

    for i in range(2, int(n**0.5) + 1):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False

    return True
```

Solution 2 (Java):

```java
public boolean isPrime(int num) {
    // If number is less than 0, 1 or even, not prime
    if (num < 0 || num <= 1 || num % 2 == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Check natural numbers till square of the number
    for (int i = 3; i * i <= num; i += 2) {
        if (num % i == 0 || num % (i + 2) == 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```

Solution 3 (C++):

```cpp
bool isPrime(int num) {
    // If number is less than 0, 1 or even, not prime
    if (num <= 1) {
        return false;
    }
    // Check all odd numbers up to the square root of the number
    for (int i = 3; i * i <= num; i += 2) {
        if (num % i == 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```

