Write function for checking BST property is valid for given binary tree

Binary search tree (BST) definition:

The binary search tree is a binary tree data structure where each node has at most two children (left and right) and the following condition is met:

The key of the node N must be greater than all keys in the left subtree and smaller than all keys in the right subtree. In other words:

* For every node: Left Subtree keys < Node key < Right subtree keys

Given a binary tree as a parameter, define a function that checks whether it is a valid binary search tree or not.

Here is an example:

```java
public class Node {
   int key;
   Node left;
   Node right;

   public Node(int key) {
       this.key = key;
       this.left = null;
       this.right = null;
   }
}

public class BstCheck {
    public boolean checkBST(Node node) {
        return checkBSTUtil(node, Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE);
    }

    private boolean checkBSTUtil(Node node, long min, long max) {
        if (node == null)
            return true;

        if (node.key <= min || node.key >= max)
            return false;

        return checkBSTUtil(node.left, min, node.key) && checkBSTUtil(node.right, node.key, max);
    }
}
```

The function `checkBST` checks whether the given binary tree is a valid binary search tree or not. `checkBSTUtil` is a helper function that recursively checks validity of binary tree by keeping track of minimum and maximum allowed values for current node given its position in binary tree (left subtree should have smaller than current node and right subtree should have greater)

Note: You can modify the Node Class or not. It's just an example.

